"Never trust anyone you can't strangle"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=setch>Setch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/31/02 8:09 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to make the familiar worthwhile, rather than a poor </span><hr size=1> What worries me about most of the enhancements you mention, is that most of them improve our sustained dps. That has to balance against something. Even if we aren't balanced now, we're not going to -achieve- a happy balance by competing for a role that's already taken. If you give us 15 more mana per second, we'll just be a little better at being crappy rogues. This is NOT where I want to see my class headed.<br>
<br>
Personally, I've had it up to _here_ with sustained dps. I'm tired of my class being measured in terms of our performance as second-rate dots.<br>
<br>
I would rather say the hell with sustained dps. Make me LAST at sustained dps. I forfeit. Give me something which will improve my performance in the thing I'm actually -useful- for: immediate, catastrophic damage.<br>
<br>
So the only one of your choices I solidly agree with is enticement. We do need more ways to reduce our resist rates.<br>
<br>
Kill the option that increases our damage per nuke. Replace it with an option that will increase both our damage and -mana- per nuke. 1.2x / 1.3x / 1.5x. Same efficiency. More impact.<br>
<br>
Kill the options that improve our mana regen and casting efficiency. Replace it with an option that gives us 10 / 25 / 33% more mana -capacity-. Bigger burns and deadlier manaburns. THAT is what we are about.<br>
<br>
If none of these will help us get into pickup groups, do we really care? I don't. I was thinking about pickup groups the other day, and realized I really don't care anymore.<br>
<br>
If my friends are online, they'll play with me because they are my friends.<br>
When they aren't online, I do not envy impersonal grind groups.<br>
Those are really just the same as soloing, but with more keystrokes.<br>
<br>
Or perhaps I'm missing something badly... but anyway that's how I feel at the moment. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ukazzap.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kazzap</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 643<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/1/02 10:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to make the familiar worthwhile, rather than a poor </span><hr size=1> My little flappy...<br>
